bill ferny x 4<br>
toldea, messenger x 2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(104)">Blade Tip</a> x 3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(103)">Black Breath</a> x 3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(72)">Goblin Runner</a>s x 2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(112)">Morgul Gates</a> x 4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(106)">Dark Whispers</a> x 1<br>
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Fellowship, generally: PATHS is clearly a very powerful card, but it&#39;s tough get the most out of it.  I&#39;ve been playing versions of this deck from the beginning, with the intent to exploit that power.  Earlier versions of this deck have always won, but have been too fragile.  I think this version has the potential to be awesome.  Unfortunately, I don&#39;t have enough time in my life to play-test very much.  The only objective in past versions was to use Bilbo to cycle PATHS into the draw deck 3 or 4 times so that, at site 9, I would have at least 2 PATHS&#39;s in my hand.  With two PATHS and a little directed archery, no more than one minion would survive the first skirmish, and frodo would survive any fierce skirmish with bounder.  With MoM and now RotEL, Bilbo, rangers, and a small fellowship are a perfect base for a choke deck.  Thus, I added No Stranger to the Shadows, Consorting with Wizards, and Elrond to help cycle through the 8 additional cards.  Consorting also gives Bilbo something productive to do before there are any PATHS to recycle.<br>
<br>
Bidding: Always bid zero.  I can&#39;t afford any burdens because I&#39;ll add 6 or 7 with PATHS over the course of the game.  Plus, with a good first draw, my nazgul might have the potential to cripple the opposing fellowship.  (Incidentally, Pippin, HOSI might replace Merry to remove a burden or heal - hmmm)<br>
<br>
Shadow, generally:  In order to be successful, I&#39;ve found I need to blow through the deck.  Hence, I&#39;ve tried to minimize the clog cards.  Blade Tip and Black Breath might end up killing someone, but it&#39;s just as important that they play quickly and easily.  Same goes for Bill Ferny and the Goblin Runners.  There&#39;s also a small effort to burden Frodo.  If my opponent bids high and doesn&#39;t get his burden removal sytem in place quickly, toldea and enquea can really cause him pain.<br>
<br>
Specific Cards:<br>
<br>
Witch King LON / Otsea - the possibility of making the King fierce, winning two skirmishes, and wounding Frodo 4 times is too much to pass up.  It&#39;s a game winner if the other side isn&#39;t prepared.<br>
<br>
Goblin runners - They don&#39;t clog your hand, they add twilight, and with Ferny&#39;s help they might win a skirmish. <br>
<br>
Gwemegil - use it liberally.  <br>
Cycling is crucial.<br>
<br>
PATHS - don&#39;t be afraid to discard it early if not necessary.  The point is to have 4 in your hand on your last turn.<br>
<br>
Weaknesses:<br>
<br>
Conditions -  Athelas protects me from blade tip / black breath, but if I don&#39;t get Elrond and Secret Sentinels, Sauron or even Moria with Armories could kill me.  I&#39;m aware of that, but I just can&#39;t make the deck any bigger.  The system depends on getting down to 5 or 6 cards in the drawdeck.<br>
<br>
Too slow - if the Nazgul fail early on, I&#39;m in trouble.  I don&#39;t have any way to triple-move, so, if the Nazzies don&#39;t step up, I&#39;ll have to blow past site 6 to site 7.  <br>
<br>
No element of surprise - That one Dark Whispers has won a surprising number of games for me, and I&#39;d like to add more.  They tend be hand cloggers though so I&#39;m reluctant.<br>
<br>
Conclusion:<br>
I really like idea of using Bilbo (or Dear Friends or Fireworks) to stack a deck for the end-game, but I want the deck to be flexible enough to win in case that strategy fails.  I know this deck can beat those Uruk/meaty fellowship decks everyone is playing, but I don&#39;t know yet whether it can do so consistently.  At least it&#39;s different. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/lotr/decks/decks.php">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/lotr/decks/decks.php?reviews=25255"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=25255" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/lotr/main/join.php">Sign up for free!</A></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
